definitions.definition: The part of Earth which is not covered by oceans or other bodies of water .
Real estate or landed property ; a partitioned and measurable area which is owned and acquired and on which buildings and structures can be built and erected .
examples: There are 50 acres of land in this estate.
They come from a faraway land .

definitions.definition: A person's country of origin and/or homeplace ; homeland .
The soil , in respect to its nature or quality for farming .
examples: good or bad land for growing potatoes
Maybe that's how it works in TV- land , but not in the real world.

definitions.definition: ( agriculture ) The ground left unploughed between furrows .
( agriculture ) Any of several portions into which a field is divided for ploughing .
( Ireland , colloquial ) A shock or fright.
examples: He got an awful land when the police arrived.

definitions.definition: ( electronics ) A conducting area on a board or chip which can be used for connecting wires .
On a compact disc or similar recording medium , an area of the medium which does not have pits .
( travel ) The non-airline portion of an itinerary. Hotel, tours, cruises, etc.
examples: Our city offices sell a lot more land than our suburban offices.

definitions.definition: ( nautical ) The lap of the strakes in a clinker-built boat ; the lap of plates in an iron vessel ; called also landing .
In any surface prepared with indentations , perforations , or grooves , that part of the surface which is not so treated, such as the level part of a millstone between the furrows.

subdefinitions.definition: ( ballistics ) The space between the rifling grooves in a gun.

definitions.definition: ( Scotland , historical ) A group of dwellings or tenements under one roof and having a common entry .
